{
  "query": "What are the benefits and drawbacks of managing water levels and features like ditches and ponds on farmland to enhance biodiversity?",
  "relevant_summary": "Managing water levels and features like ditches and ponds on farmland shows both positive and negative effects for biodiversity enhancement. Benefits include increased invertebrate biomass or abundance, plant species richness, emergent plant cover, amphibian diversity and abundance, bird visit rates and higher numbers of some bird species from managing ditches under agri-environment schemes (Action 135). Raising water levels in ditches or grassland was associated with increased bird numbers, breeding bird numbers, plant species that favour wet conditions, and invertebrate numbers or biomass in agricultural landscapes (Action 121). Additionally, higher plant diversity was found on ditch banks along unsprayed edges compared to those sprayed with pesticides (Action 135). For pond management, maintaining pond water levels increased natterjack toad populations or maintained newt populations (Action 833) and enabled successful breeding by dusky gopher frogs (Action 833). However, drawbacks were also identified. Some studies found that ditch management had negative or no clear effects on some farmland bird species or plants (Action 135). Raising water levels resulted in a net loss of plant species and did not affect lapwing foraging rate (Action 121). Unflooded pastures contained a high biomass of soil macroinvertebrates of importance to breeding wading birds (Action 121). Additionally, re-wetting soils on old arable fields was not an effective method of reducing nutrient levels and restoring species-rich grassland (Action 121). One study found that draining ponds, particularly in the summer, significantly increased abundance and numbers of amphibian species, suggesting that permanent water levels may not always be optimal (Action 833).",
