{"query": "What is the evidence for the effectiveness of creating or managing linear features like hedges and beetle banks for farmland wildlife?", "summary": "Evidence shows that linear features like hedges and beetle banks provide varying benefits to farmland wildlife. For beetle banks, studies found positive effects on invertebrate densities and ground beetle density and species diversity in spring and summer, though effects varied between specific grass species and invertebrate groups (Action 651). Beetle banks also supported higher densities of harvest mouse nests compared to field margins (Actions 2393, 651). However, some studies found lower or no difference in invertebrate densities on beetle banks relative to other habitats (Action 651). For birds, beetle banks showed mixed results - some evidence indicated birds used beetle banks and positive effects when combined with other conservation measures, while other studies found no farmland bird species associated with beetle banks (Action 651). Studies on butterflies and moths found that beetle banks had lower species richness of butterflies compared to hedgerows (Action 3927).

For hedgerows, evidence demonstrates stronger benefits. Newly planted hedges showed higher abundance, species richness and diversity of beetles and spiders compared to crop fields or field margins (Action 538). Established hedgerows had higher species richness of butterflies and macro-moths than beetle banks, crops or pasture (Action 3976). The abundance of butterflies, moths and macro-moths was higher along hedgerows than on beetle banks, grass margins, or field interiors (Action 3976). Hedgerows also increased small mammal abundance when established alongside arable land (Action 2383). For reptiles, cultivated areas with hedges had reptile communities more similar to forests than areas without hedges (Action 3519). Additionally, hedges trimmed three or more years prior had more bat species and higher activity of certain bat species than recently trimmed hedges (Action 1943).

Field margins provided additional evidence - uncropped cultivated margins benefited target farmland bird species, plants, invertebrates and mammals, including increased species richness and abundance across multiple taxa (Action 562). Plant diversity in field margins increased soprano pipistrelle and barbastelle bat activity (Action 1941).", "action_ids": ["2393","651","3976","3927","538","3519","2383","1943","562","1941"]}

